@node not23 "T-ZER0: A SHOOT-EM-UP TO END ALL THE SHOOT-EM-UPS"

T-ZER0: A SHOOT-EM-UP TO END ALL THE SHOOT-EM-UPS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

After  the  big success of their past games Capital Punishment, Myst, Quake, and
more  recently  Napalm,  clickBOOM  is  about  to release their next big seller:
T-zer0.

T-zer0,  previously  known  as Trauma Zero, is a shoot'em up much in the line of
classics  as  R-Type or SWIV. It has been in development for two years now by an
italian group and hopefully it is nearly finished.

T-zer0  is  played  in  either  Story  mode, Arcade mode or Battle mode with you
taking  control  of one of the three crafts (there is also some hidden ones). It
will have a simultaneous two player mode and contains a massive array of weapons
(over   50   available   such   as  Guns,  Laser,  Side-Shot,  Plasma,  Missile,
Homing-Missile, etc) and it is full of enemies such as big end of level bosses.

It  will  feature  a real time animated background with 256 colours at 25 Hz and
have real time translucency effects like the fire of a missile or the background
around  an  explosion.  It  will  include  a  lot  of  speech, awesome animation
sequences  (including intro and between levels), incredible graphics and tons of
sprites on screen along with 1/4 pixel scrolling.

The current list of specifications are:

   * 50fps 1/4 pixel scroll;
   * insane number of sprites;
   * adjustable transparencies;
   * power-up galore;
   * few 100Mb of intro+between level movies;
   * free, full level editor, used to create the game, included on the CD;
   * two choices of powerups (high-tech, classic arcade);
   * a lot of speech;
   * two choices of cd music high-tech (techno/trance), arcade (pop);
   * 1/2 players;
   * several endings;
   * hidden aircraft/levels;

T-zer0  will  require  an  Amiga AGA, 8 Mb RAM, 030, 45 Mb HD and CD. Sadly, the
game  is going to be AGA only, so it will not support GFX cards. This is because
that  only  the  direct  use  of  the AGA chips allows a huge number of sprites,
backgrounds, explosions and everything else.

It is planned that the game will be released at the end of July, just in time to
be  premiered  at  the  World  of  Amiga  show  in London. It is expected that a
playable demo is going to be released soon.

For more information, please visit clickboom.com/t0
